1470–":"circa 1470–Overleden","1480–Female":"1480–Overleden","1500–1582":"1500–1582","1470–Male":"1470–Overleden","Abt 1470":"circa 1470","1500":"1500","abt. 1500":"circa 1500","about 1501":"circa 1501","1582":"1582","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","Talla, Peebles, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scotland":"Schotland","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Schotland"},"en":{"Abt 1470–":"about 1470–Deceased","1480–Female":"1480–Deceased","1500–1582":"1500–1582","1470–Male":"1470–Deceased","Abt 1470":"about 1470","1500":"1500","abt. 1500":"about 1500","about 1501":"about 1501","1582":"1582","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","Talla, Peebles, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English (northern; of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in Normandy called <i>La Haie</i> or <i>La Haye</i> (Old French <i>haie</i> ‘hedge, enclosure’, ‘forest for hunting deer and other animals’, a borrowing of the ancient Germanic word <i>haga</i>). Robert <i>de Haia</i> or <i>de la Haye</i> is known to have come from La Haye-du-Puits in Manche; he was the founder of Boxgrove Priory in Sussex (1123), and holder of the Honor of Halnaker (Sussex) and (by marriage) the barony of Kolswein (Lincolnshire). The Norman name was also taken to Ireland, where it has since flourished in the county of Wexford as <i>Hay</i> and   Hayes  . Elsewhere in Ireland the name usually has a native Irish origin, see below.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>hay(e)</i>, <i>heye</i>, <i>heghe</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>(ge)hæg</i>) or ‘forest fenced off for hunting’ (Old French <i>haie</i>); or else a habitational name from a place so called, such as Hay (in Herefordshire and Westmorland) or Hey in Scammonden (Yorkshire). It was no doubt sometimes synonymous with   Hayward  .","English: nickname for a tall man, from Middle English <i>heigh</i>, <i>hey</i>, <i>high</i> ‘high, tall’ (Old English <i>hēah</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"High","meanings":["English:","nickname for a tall man, from Middle English <i>heigh</i>, <i>hey</i>, <i>high</i> ‘high, tall’ (Old English <i>hēah</i>). Compare   Hay   3.","topographic name for someone who lived ‘(on the) height or hill’, from Middle English <i>heigh</i> ‘height, hilltop’ (Old English <i>hēah</i>). Compare   Hight  ."]},{"name":"Hai","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Abdul, Syed, Arifa, Atta, Faiz, Hamid, Iftekhar, Iskandar, Mohamed, Mohammad, Mohannad.  Vietnamese Mui, Pham, Tran, Vo, Bui, Cao, Chau, Dinh, Duong, Nguyen, Sau, Vo Van.  Jewish Ilan, Ronen, Shlomo.  Chinese Chan, Chiming, Lung, Wai Fun, Yin.","Muslim (mainly the Indian subcontinent): from a personal name based on Arabic <i>ḥayy</i> ‘alive’. <i>Al-Ḥayy</i> ‘the Living’ is an attribute of Allah.","Jewish: variant of   Hay  ."]},{"name":"Dehay","meanings":["French: topographic name, with fused preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’, for someone who lived by an enclosure, from the masculine form of Old French <i>haye</i> ‘hedge’; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word (see   Hay   9).","Altered form (also <b>De Hay</b>) of Dutch <b>De Haij</b> or <b>De Haaij</b>, which is probably of French origin (see above)."]},{"name":"Haig","meanings":["Scottish and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of various places in northern France named with Old Norse <i>hagi</i> ‘enclosure’, a word with cognates in most ancient Germanic languages. Compare   Hay  . The Haigs of Bemersyde in Berwickshire derive their name from the district of La Hague in Manche.","Scottish and Irish (Cavan): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Thaoig</b> and <b>Mac Thaidhg</b> (see   McCaig  )."]},{"name":"Hayman","meanings":["English: topographic name probably from Middle English <i>hai(e)</i>, <i>hei(e)</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>(ge)hæg</i>), denoting a dweller by an enclosure (see   Hay   2 ), or else a nickname for a ‘keeper of the enclosure’ (compare   Hayward  ).","English: nickname for a tall man, from Middle English <i>heigh</i>, <i>high(e)</i> (Old English <i>hēah</i>); see also   Hay   3.","English: occupational name for a seller of hay, from Middle English <i>hai</i>, <i>hei</i> (Old English <i>hēg</i>, <i>hīg</i>)."]},{"name":"Hayes","meanings":["Irish (Cork): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hAodha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Aodh</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘fire’. Compare   McCoy  . In some cases especially in County Wexford, the surname is of English origin (see below), having been taken to Ireland by the Normans.","English: variant of   Hay  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: topographic name from the plural form of Middle English <i>hay(e)</i>, <i>heye</i>, <i>heghe</i> ‘enclosure’ (see   Hay  ), sometimes used as a collective noun for a farm, especially in Devon, where it is a frequent minor placename. Compare   Hain  ."]},{"name":"Haycock","meanings":["English: from a pet form of the Middle English personal name <i>Hai</i> + <i>coc</i>; see   Hay   4 and compare   Cocke  ."]},{"name":"Haylett","meanings":["English (Norfolk): from a pet form (double diminutive) of the personal name <i>Hai</i> (see   Hay   4), from <i>Hai</i> + <i>-el</i> + <i>-ot</i>."]},{"name":"Hey","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Hay  .","Dutch: variant, mostly Americanized (or archaic) and Flemish, of <b>Heij</b>, a topographic name for someone who lived on a heath, Dutch <i>hei</i>, <i>heide</i>.","German: metonymic occupational name for a grower or mower of grass, from Middle High German <i>höu</i> ‘grass, hay’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Hay was born about 1470, in Peeblesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. He married Sommervels about 1501, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1470–":"umbes 1470–Surnud","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","1500–1582":"1500–1582","1470–Male":"1470–Surnud","Abt 1470":"umbes 1470","1500":"1500","abt. 1500":"umbes 1500","about 1501":"umbes 1501","1582":"1582","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","Talla, Peebles, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"Abt 1470–":"noin 1470–Kuollut","1480–Female":"1480–Kuollut","1500–1582":"1500–1582","1470–Male":"1470–Kuollut","Abt 1470":"noin 1470","1500":"1500","abt. 1500":"noin 1500","about 1501":"noin 1501","1582":"1582","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","Talla, Peebles, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Scotland","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"Abt 1470–":"environ 1470–Décédé","1480–Female":"1480–Décédée","1500–1582":"1500–1582","1470–Male":"1470–Décédé","Abt 1470":"environ 1470","1500":"1500","abt. 1500":"environ 1500","about 1501":"environ 1501","1582":"1582","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","Talla, Peebles, Scotland":"Valle de Twede, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Scotland":"Écosse","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Hay est né environ 1470, à Valle de Twede, Écosse, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé Sommervels environ 1501, à Écosse. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"Abt 1470–":"um 1470–Verstorben","1480–Female":"1480–Verstorben","1500–1582":"1500–1582","1470–Male":"1470–Verstorben","Abt 1470":"um 1470","1500":"1500","abt. 1500":"um 1500","about 1501":"um 1501","1582":"1582","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","Talla, Peebles, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Schottland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","lifeSummary":"Hay wurde um 1470 in Peeblesshire, Schottland, United Kingdom geboren. Er hat um 1501 in Scotland Sommervel